# Workflow Conventions

This skill documents the canonical conventions for requests, tasks, tags, and status lifecycles in the Lucent workflow system.

## When to Use This Skill

Reference this skill when:
- Creating or processing requests and tasks
- Applying tags to memories or work items
- Implementing workflow automation or validation
- Debugging stuck or incorrectly-routed work
- Writing code that interacts with the request/task tracking system

## Tag Conventions

### Canonical Tag Names

Use these exact tag names — consistency is critical for routing and visibility:

| Tag | Meaning | Applied When |
|-----|---------|--------------|
| `needs-review` | Item requires human review/approval | Work ready for review (NOT `awaiting-approval` or other variants) |
| `daemon` | Created/managed by daemon | All daemon-created memories and work items |
| `feedback-approved` | Human approved this item | Review queue: user clicks "approve" |
| `feedback-rejected` | Human rejected this item | Review queue: user clicks "reject" |
| `feedback-processed` | Feedback has been processed by daemon | After daemon acts on approval/rejection |
| `validated` | Pattern/approach confirmed as good | After processing approved feedback |
| `rejection-lesson` | Learn from this rejection | After analyzing rejected feedback |
| `pending` | Work item waiting to start | Initial state for daemon tasks (deprecated for tracked tasks) |
| `claimed-by-{instance_id}` | Task claimed by specific daemon | After atomic claim operation |

### Deprecated/Incorrect Tags

**Never use:**
- `awaiting-approval` → Use `needs-review` instead
- `awaiting-review` → Use `needs-review` instead
- Any custom approval tag → Use `needs-review` instead

## Status Lifecycles

### Request Status Flow

```
pending → in_progress → completed
                      → failed
```

| Status | Meaning | Transitions |
|--------|---------|-------------|
| `pending` | Request created, not yet started | → `in_progress` when first task starts |
| `in_progress` | At least one task is active | → `completed` when all tasks succeed |
| | | → `failed` when any task fails |
| `completed` | All tasks finished successfully | Terminal state |
| `failed` | One or more tasks failed | Terminal state |

### Task Status Flow

```
pending/planned → claimed → running → completed
                                   → failed
```

| Status | Meaning | Transitions |
|--------|---------|-------------|
| `pending` | Task created, ready to claim | → `claimed` via atomic claim |
| `planned` | Task created but not yet ready | → `claimed` via atomic claim |
| `claimed` | Daemon has claimed this task | → `running` when agent starts |
| `running` | Agent actively executing task | → `completed` with result |
| | | → `failed` with error |
| `completed` | Task finished successfully | Terminal state |
| `failed` | Task failed with error | Terminal state |

**Important**: 
- `claim_task` is atomic — only one daemon can claim each task
- Tasks stuck in `claimed` for >30 minutes are auto-released via stale release mechanism
- `complete_task` and `fail_task` should only transition from `running` or `claimed` (validation gap noted)

## Agent Type Validation

### Available Agent Types

Only these agent types are valid when creating tasks:

| Agent Type | Description | Model Default |
|------------|-------------|---------------|
| `research` | Deep investigation, web access, synthesis | claude-sonnet-4 |
| `code` | Technical implementation, file operations | claude-sonnet-4 |
| `memory` | Memory maintenance, consolidation | claude-haiku-4.5 |
| `reflection` | Self-analysis, behavioral review | claude-sonnet-4 |
| `documentation` | Docs, guides, knowledge bases | claude-sonnet-4 |
| `planning` | Goal decomposition, roadmaps | claude-sonnet-4 |
| `assessment` | Environment discovery, role adaptation | gemini-3-pro-preview |

**Validation**: `create_task` validates agent_type against approved definitions in `.github/agents/definitions/`. Invalid types are rejected with error message.

## Context Passing Conventions

### Parent Request Context

Every task receives:
1. **Parent request description** — the original work request
2. **Sibling task results** — completed results from other tasks in the same request

This is fetched via `get_request_context(request_id)` and passed to the agent prompt.

### Size Limits

- **Total context**: ~30KB maximum
- **Per-task result**: ~8KB maximum (truncated with "[truncated]" marker)
- Results exceeding limits are trimmed to avoid token bloat

### Format

```markdown
--- PARENT REQUEST ---
Title: <request title>
Description: <request description>

--- COMPLETED SIBLING TASK RESULTS ---
## Task: <task title> (completed)
Model: <model> | Agent: <agent_type>

<task result text>
```

### When Context Is Passed

- **Sequential tasks**: Later tasks see results from earlier completed tasks
- **Parallel tasks**: Tasks running simultaneously don't see each other's results until next task in sequence
- **Failed tasks**: Failure messages are NOT passed to siblings (only successful completions)

## Review Routing Rules

### How Items Enter Review Queue

1. **Tag with `needs-review`**: Any memory or work item tagged `needs-review` appears in review queue
2. **Visibility**: Item must be `shared=True` for org members to see it in queue
3. **Daemon memories**: Automatically shared (`shared=True` forced for daemon-created memories)

### Review Actions

| Action | Result | Wake Signal |
|--------|--------|-------------|
| Approve | Add `feedback-approved` tag | `pg_notify('request_ready')` fired → daemon wakes immediately |
| Reject | Add `feedback-rejected` tag | `pg_notify('request_ready')` fired → daemon wakes immediately |

### Processing Approved Feedback

When daemon finds `feedback-approved` memories:
1. Read the approved content carefully
2. **If it contains actionable items** (findings to fix, plans to implement):
   - Create tracked request via `create_request`
   - Break into tasks via `create_task` with appropriate agent assignments
   - Approval means "go ahead and do this" — not just acknowledgment
3. Tag memory with `feedback-processed` and `validated`
4. Note the validated pattern for future reference

### Processing Rejected Feedback

When daemon finds `feedback-rejected` memories:
1. Read rejection reason carefully
2. Create self-improvement memory analyzing what went wrong
3. Cancel or revise any dependent pending tasks
4. Tag memory with `feedback-processed` and `rejection-lesson`

## Deduplication Rules

### Before Creating Requests

**CRITICAL**: Before creating any new request, check `list_active_work()` to see ALL non-completed requests and their status.

**Deduplication logic**:
- If existing request covers the same goal → don't create duplicate
- If existing request needs more tasks → add tasks to it via `create_task`
- If existing request is in progress → wait for completion
- If existing request is stuck/stale → investigate why rather than creating parallel effort

**Why this matters**: Without deduplication, cognitive loop creates duplicate work items, wasting resources and confusing task queue.

### Before Creating Tasks

Check if the parent request already has tasks covering this work. If so, update task description or status rather than creating duplicates.

## Special Workflows

### Scheduled Work

Schedules create requests automatically when they fire:
- Request source is set to `schedule:<schedule_id>`
- Original schedule title/description flows to request
- Task agent_type, model, priority come from schedule definition

### Feedback Processing Pipeline

1. User approves/rejects item in review queue
2. Web API adds `feedback-approved` or `feedback-rejected` tag
3. Web API fires `pg_notify('request_ready')` with feedback payload
4. Daemon cognitive loop wakes immediately (no 15-min wait)
5. Daemon searches for feedback tags and processes FIRST (before new work)
6. Daemon creates tasks if approved content is actionable
7. Daemon tags memory with `feedback-processed`

### Stale Task Release

- Tasks stuck in `claimed` status for >30 minutes are auto-released
- Release sets status back to `pending` and clears `claimed_by`, `claimed_at`
- Prevents daemon crashes from permanently locking tasks

## Common Issues and Solutions

### Issue: Duplicate requests created

**Symptom**: Multiple requests with similar titles/descriptions
**Root Cause**: Cognitive loop not checking `list_active_work` before creating requests
**Solution**: Always call `list_active_work()` in perceive phase and compare before creating

### Issue: Tasks never picked up

**Symptom**: Task stays in `pending` forever
**Root Cause**: Invalid agent_type or task not visible to daemon
**Solution**: Verify agent_type against available definitions, check task query filters

### Issue: Review items not visible

**Symptom**: Tagged `needs-review` but not in review queue
**Root Cause**: Memory not shared (`shared=False`)
**Solution**: Ensure daemon-created memories use `shared=True` (automatic), user-created memories set `shared=True` explicitly if needed

### Issue: No wake on approval

**Symptom**: 15-minute delay before daemon processes approval
**Root Cause**: `pg_notify` not fired or daemon not listening
**Solution**: Verify web API calls `pg_notify('request_ready')` after approval/rejection

